{"key":"processedPost-17778175","value":{"id":17778175,"first":17745082,"last":26684042,"when":1360535668,"utime":"02/11/13 12:34 AM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><b>infected_2 said:</b><br /><br />It also might be due to twist n pull. It damages the substrate which it will have to use energy to repair.<br /></blockquote><br /><br />Almost.<br />The problem is the substrate doesn't use energy to repair damage from improper picking.&nbsp; The damaged area sits exposed until mold spores land and grow on it.&nbsp; This is why you should only twist off mushrooms that are very loosely attached.&nbsp; If a mushroom is firmly anchored to the substrate, cut off with a sharp knife, scissors, fishing line in a loop where you pull the ends to make the cut, etc.&nbsp; There is no need to remove the stump and doing so leads to stalled fruiting and mold.<br />RR","title":"Re: Growth Stops After I Pick A Mushroom."}}